147
00:14:29.526 --> 00:14:32.806
But what about the haystack? And the haystack is obviously KRAS.

148
00:14:34.266 --> 00:14:37.906
Why is it undruggable? I agree with Anirban we should retire the word soon,

149
00:14:38.106 --> 00:14:41.626
but essentially, there's a high affinity of KRAS for

150
00:14:41.706 --> 00:14:45.626
GTP. It's tightly bound, and the KRAS proteins

151
00:14:45.646 --> 00:14:49.456
have a smooth surface and an absence of a binding pocket, and that's why it's been

152
00:14:49.486 --> 00:14:51.406
so hard to drug this target.

153
00:14:52.586 --> 00:14:54.566
But how do we go about cracking KRAS?

154
00:14:54.596 --> 00:14:58.566
So the way I see it, it's a dam, and we are blowing up the dam in different places.

155
00:14:59.326 --> 00:15:02.026
And we are truly cracking KRAS now.

156
00:15:02.846 --> 00:15:05.806
And this is a chart of KRAS drug discovery

157
00:15:06.526 --> 00:15:10.486
identified in the 1960s and '70s. 2013, I'm

158
00:15:10.495 --> 00:15:14.126
going to talk about some breakthroughs, and now we are at 2025,

159
00:15:14.366 --> 00:15:18.186
2026, really leading the charge to changing the

160
00:15:18.226 --> 00:15:20.826
treatment outcomes for our patients with this disease.

161
00:15:22.166 --> 00:15:23.826
So first of all, in 2013,

162
00:15:25.106 --> 00:15:27.226
it changed from undruggable to druggable.

163
00:15:28.086 --> 00:15:31.926
Kevin Shawcat's group found this binding pocket in the switch II region

164
00:15:32.006 --> 00:15:35.246
of G12C. We had G12C

