tumor microenvironment that really typifies this disease, as

473
00:33:17.234 --> 00:33:21.134
well as the low to intermediate mutational burden that is common in

474
00:33:21.214 --> 00:33:25.114
pancreatic cancer, really, and then postulated that perhaps there

475
00:33:25.134 --> 00:33:28.234
were just no neoantigens to actually see.

476
00:33:29.094 --> 00:33:32.634
As we've already heard, that myth is starting to get busted.

477
00:33:33.114 --> 00:33:36.944
Work from my own group, Vinod Balachandran, Steve Rosenberg, and many

478
00:33:36.974 --> 00:33:40.684
others, have really demonstrated that a subset of

479
00:33:40.714 --> 00:33:43.823
pancreatic cancer patients do in fact harbor at least

480
00:33:43.874 --> 00:33:46.894
predicted high-quality neoantigens.

481
00:33:47.334 --> 00:33:51.074
We've seen tremendously exciting efforts, early-stage

482
00:33:51.134 --> 00:33:54.534
clinical efforts, but demonstrating that it is possible to

483
00:33:54.594 --> 00:33:58.014
elicit robust tumor-specific T cell

484
00:33:58.054 --> 00:34:02.024
responses in this disease. And while small number

485
00:34:02.054 --> 00:34:05.424
of patients, I think very, very compelling data coming out

486
00:34:05.954 --> 00:34:09.874
demonstrating that cellular therapies can actually function

487
00:34:09.894 --> 00:34:13.513
in pancreatic cancer using neoantigen-directed

488
00:34:13.614 --> 00:34:17.094
TCR-engineered T cells or TCR T cells.

489
00:34:18.054 --> 00:34:21.734
So with this in mind, we said, well, if we're going to

490
00:34:21.774 --> 00:34:25.665
really develop effective antigen-directed therapies,

491
00:34:25.734 --> 00:34:29.674
we actually need to understand what this peptide HLA

492
00:34:29.834 --> 00:34:33.294
complex actually looks like and describe the antigen

493
00:34:33.354 --> 00:34:35.394
landscape in pancreatic cancer.

494
00:34:36.214 --> 00:34:39.854
So if we think about the tumor antigen landscape more broadly

495
00:34:39.995 --> 00:34:43.714
across cancer, we've focused over the past many years on

496
00:34:43.754 --> 00:34:47.194
cancer-associated viruses, obviously don't really play a role here for pancreas

497
00:34:47.274 --> 00:34:51.234
cancer, but on tumor-associated antigens and somatic

498
00:34:51.314 --> 00:34:54.354
mutations, and seen tremendous excitement in those.

499
00:34:54.894 --> 00:34:58.574
But what I'd like to introduce at the beginning here is that we're really just

500
00:34:58.613 --> 00:35:02.274
scratching the surface of the targetable tumor antigen

501
00:35:02.314 --> 00:35:06.174
landscape. The past couple years from many

502
00:35:06.294 --> 00:35:09.774
groups have shown actually that cancer cells more broadly,

503
00:35:09.814 --> 00:35:13.494
including now pancreatic cancer, that they go haywire, not just

504
00:35:13.574 --> 00:35:17.434
transcriptionally, but also translationally, that you start

505
00:35:17.474 --> 00:35:20.574
translating areas of the putatively

506
00:35:20.774 --> 00:35:22.374
non-protein coding genome.

507
00:35:23.354 --> 00:35:27.144
This can include these novel unannotated open reading frames,

508
00:35:27.574 --> 00:35:31.414
as well as endogenous retroviruses, other transposable

509
00:35:31.514 --> 00:35:35.274
elements that can both be transcriptionally misregulated, but

510
00:35:35.334 --> 00:35:39.094
also be translated, giving rise to HLA-1 bound

511
00:35:39.104 --> 00:35:42.474
peptides in cancer. And really elegant work from Reuven

512
00:35:42.494 --> 00:35:46.454
Agami's group has actually demonstrated that under certain stress

513
00:35:46.574 --> 00:35:49.594
conditions, cancer cells actually recurrently

514
00:35:49.694 --> 00:35:53.134
misincorporate the wrong amino acid, leading to

515
00:35:53.334 --> 00:35:57.054
non-genetically templated missense mutations that

516
00:35:57.134 --> 00:35:59.234
actually can be recognized by T cells.

517
00:35:59.854 --> 00:36:03.474
Let me spend the next few minutes talking about our work

518
00:36:03.754 --> 00:36:07.234
actually on these novel unannotated open reading

519
00:36:07.374 --> 00:36:09.394
frames in pancreatic cancer.

520
00:36:10.794 --> 00:36:14.354
So how do we get there? Again, we want to actually ask,

521
00:36:14.734 --> 00:36:18.374
instead of just computational predictions, what if we

522
00:36:18.494 --> 00:36:21.834
use newer technologies, including mass spec technologies, to

523
00:36:21.874 --> 00:36:25.734
directly survey the antigen landscape in this disease?

524
00:36:26.314 --> 00:36:30.094
So we took a number of patient biospecimens, either direct from patients or

525
00:36:30.214 --> 00:36:31.874
patient-derived organoids,

526
00:36:32.674 --> 00:36:36.494
did extensive genomic and transcriptomic profiling on these,

527
00:36:36.994 --> 00:36:40.594
ultimately followed by immunoprecipitation of

528
00:36:40.834 --> 00:36:44.754
HLA class II complexes, elution of peptides, followed

529
00:36:44.794 --> 00:36:48.634
by mass spec, a process termed immunopeptidomics.

530
00:36:49.054 --> 00:36:52.674
And this is just to highlight that this is a large collaborative effort among many

531
00:36:52.754 --> 00:36:56.474
groups at the Hale Family Center for Pancreatic Cancer Research,

532
00:36:56.854 --> 00:37:00.390
as well as close colleagues at MIT.The

533
00:37:00.430 --> 00:37:04.250
immunopeptidomics, the mass spec part of it, was all done at the

534
00:37:04.330 --> 00:37:08.050
Broad Institute through the proteomics platform there, and really

535
00:37:08.130 --> 00:37:10.430
spearheaded by Steve Carr and Jen Abelin.

536
00:37:10.950 --> 00:37:14.350
And we were excited to see that we were able to get tremendous

537
00:37:14.690 --> 00:37:18.570
depth of profiling, now directly detecting anywhere

538
00:37:18.610 --> 00:37:21.710
between 8,000 to over 18,000

539
00:37:22.070 --> 00:37:25.630
unique class I associated peptides per patient

540
00:37:25.730 --> 00:37:26.110
sample.

541
00:37:26.950 --> 00:37:30.370
But beyond just the depth. Because we had whole genome

542
00:37:30.430 --> 00:37:33.840
sequencing, we were able to do mutation calls, HLA typing, and

543
00:37:33.950 --> 00:37:37.830
create a personalized proteogenomic search space on

544
00:37:37.950 --> 00:37:41.850
each and every patient, and now actually, very rewardingly,

545
00:37:42.230 --> 00:37:44.970
directly detect mutation-encoded

546
00:37:45.030 --> 00:37:48.990
neoepitopes on this disease, really fitting with many of

547
00:37:49.070 --> 00:37:52.480
ours and others' computational predictions, which was very

548
00:37:52.830 --> 00:37:53.390
exciting.

549
00:37:54.330 --> 00:37:56.370
On the other hand, it was also very humbling.

550
00:37:57.150 --> 00:38:00.950
If we look at the number of exonic mutations that we're

551
00:38:00.990 --> 00:38:04.910
able to detect by whole genome sequencing, here on the left, compared to

552
00:38:04.950 --> 00:38:08.870
the number of mutation-encoded neoepitopes detectable by mass spec on

553
00:38:08.910 --> 00:38:12.810
the right, they're few and far between, despite the profound depth that we're

554
00:38:12.930 --> 00:38:16.680
getting. And so we started asking ourselves, well, clearly mutations

555
00:38:16.850 --> 00:38:20.630
are targets for the subset of patients that have them, but what about the

556
00:38:20.890 --> 00:38:23.970
patients where we can't actually empirically detect

557
00:38:24.030 --> 00:38:27.910
mutation-encoded neoepitopes? The time was right that

558
00:38:27.970 --> 00:38:31.950
Cathy Wu, Aviv Regev, Claude Perrault, and others had begun

559
00:38:31.990 --> 00:38:35.630
describing in other tumor types this concept of novel,

560
00:38:35.890 --> 00:38:39.590
unannotated open reading frames in cancer, these so-called new

561
00:38:39.730 --> 00:38:43.550
ORFs. Just briefly, I've introduced the overall dark proteome, but these

562
00:38:43.590 --> 00:38:47.330
are thought to arise from aberrant translation

563
00:38:47.970 --> 00:38:51.120
outside of annotated protein coding genomes.

564
00:38:51.790 --> 00:38:55.670
So we can think about translation of the five-prime or three-prime

565
00:38:55.790 --> 00:38:59.710
UTR, translation in the wrong reading frame, these so-called

566
00:38:59.970 --> 00:39:03.630
intORFs, and importantly, this is not due to a frame-shifting mutation,

567
00:39:03.990 --> 00:39:07.930
but actually ribosomal promiscuity, so translation in the plus

568
00:39:07.990 --> 00:39:11.770
one or plus two reading frame, translation of link RNAs,

569
00:39:11.910 --> 00:39:15.810
and many others. So with this in mind, we augmented our

570
00:39:15.850 --> 00:39:19.490
proteomic search space to see whether this was actually true in pancreatic cancer.

571
00:39:19.550 --> 00:39:21.210
Lo and behold, it was, of course.

572
00:39:22.050 --> 00:39:25.570
Instead of one or two peptides per patient sample, now we're

573
00:39:25.590 --> 00:39:29.430
detecting tens to hundreds, and actually in every patient sample that we

574
00:39:29.490 --> 00:39:33.270
look at, making up anywhere between about 2% to over

575
00:39:33.370 --> 00:39:36.510
8% of the overall immunopeptidome.

576
00:39:37.470 --> 00:39:41.270
Now, these fell into a number of different defined categories or biotypes, and we

577
00:39:41.290 --> 00:39:44.230
saw a clear predilection in pancreatic cancer for

578
00:39:44.410 --> 00:39:48.290
translation of five-prime UTRs, and then these

579
00:39:48.310 --> 00:39:52.070
intORFs, so translation in alternative reading frames, but

580
00:39:52.110 --> 00:39:55.610
clear evidence for a number of these different new ORF

581
00:39:55.750 --> 00:39:58.770
biotypes in patient-derived organoids.

582
00:39:59.490 --> 00:40:02.350
Now, to make sure, though, that this was not some artifact of

583
00:40:02.430 --> 00:40:06.070
organotypic culture, we went back to bulk

584
00:40:06.090 --> 00:40:09.990
tumors directly out of the patient right after Whipple resection and put these

585
00:40:10.010 --> 00:40:13.830
through the identical immunopeptidomic workflow, and we're

586
00:40:13.930 --> 00:40:17.350
really pleased to see that, in fact, we could see the same

587
00:40:17.470 --> 00:40:21.330
non-canonical open reading frame translation was

588
00:40:21.370 --> 00:40:25.170
preserved in the primary tumors, and many of the peptides are

589
00:40:25.230 --> 00:40:29.170
actually shared between bulk tumors and organoids, even despite

590
00:40:29.180 --> 00:40:31.330
the fact that these are from different patients.

591
00:40:32.670 --> 00:40:34.930
So this was all exciting, and we said, "Well, great.

592
00:40:35.010 --> 00:40:38.730
We've detected these cryptic peptides or these non-canonical peptides in

593
00:40:38.810 --> 00:40:42.650
pancreatic cancer." But honestly, these had been well worked out in other

594
00:40:42.690 --> 00:40:46.340
tumor types before this. So we took a bit of a step back and said, "Well, what is

595
00:40:46.550 --> 00:40:50.230
not known about this field of the dark

596
00:40:50.330 --> 00:40:54.310
proteome more broadly?" And a number of questions were unanswered

597
00:40:54.350 --> 00:40:58.190
at that time, and we'll go through them, that we've tried to answer

598
00:40:58.250 --> 00:41:01.940
each one in line. The first being,

599
00:41:02.210 --> 00:41:05.970
what is the real evidence that these non-canonical or

600
00:41:06.010 --> 00:41:08.310
cryptic peptides are truly tumor specific?

601
00:41:09.090 --> 00:41:12.990
They're outside of annotated protein coding genes, but it's people like

602
00:41:13.090 --> 00:41:16.229
us that do these annotations, and so did we just get the annotations wrong?

603
00:41:17.450 --> 00:41:21.290
The other is, what is the mechanism of non-canonical ORF

604
00:41:21.330 --> 00:41:23.510
translation in cancer more broadly?

605
00:41:24.310 --> 00:41:28.210
And then can these actually, we know they're presented on HLA class 1, but can

606
00:41:28.230 --> 00:41:32.130
they be recognized by CD8 T cells? Are these really immunogenic?

607
00:41:32.170 --> 00:41:35.750
And if so, what's the real therapeutic potential for

608
00:41:35.810 --> 00:41:36.570
targeting these?

609
00:41:37.970 --> 00:41:39.970
So first, to assess tumor specificity.

610
00:41:40.390 --> 00:41:43.310
Because these are thought to arise from aberrant

611
00:41:43.330 --> 00:41:46.730
translation in cancer, we wanted to create a

612
00:41:46.810 --> 00:41:50.610
translation-centric view of healthy tissues, and

613
00:41:50.690 --> 00:41:54.190
here, using a few hundred healthy tissues profiled

614
00:41:54.230 --> 00:41:57.740
by HLA class 1 immunopeptidomics, as well as

615
00:41:57.850 --> 00:42:01.590
ribosome sequencing, spanning 28 different organ

616
00:42:01.650 --> 00:42:03.530
systems, including healthy thymus.

617
00:42:04.030 --> 00:42:07.910
We asked the question, can we detect any evidence of these

618
00:42:08.030 --> 00:42:11.100
non-canonical open reading frames in healthy tissues?

619
00:42:11.600 --> 00:42:13.970
And the first takeaway was that some we can.

620
00:42:14.330 --> 00:42:17.630
So meaning many of these are actually likely

621
00:42:17.730 --> 00:42:20.850
misannotations and do occur in healthy tissues.

622
00:42:21.270 --> 00:42:25.030
However, for about 500, a little over a third of these, we could find

623
00:42:25.270 --> 00:42:28.990
zero evidence of translation in any healthy tissue that we

624
00:42:29.470 --> 00:42:32.050
profiled, and now we've profiled many more since then.

625
00:42:33.010 --> 00:42:36.880
And so we termed these cancer-restricted cryptic

626
00:42:36.950 --> 00:42:39.590
peptides or cancer-restricted cryptic antigens.

627
00:42:40.090 --> 00:42:43.870
What got us excited about this is not just that they are specific to cancer,

628
00:42:44.270 --> 00:42:47.970
but that they're often shared across patients, unlike many

629
00:42:48.030 --> 00:42:51.738
mutation-encoded neoepitopes.These are shared, of course, by

630
00:42:51.838 --> 00:42:54.758
patients with the correct HLA restriction element.

631
00:42:55.178 --> 00:42:58.818
But in HLA-A*02:01, we found about half of our

632
00:42:58.898 --> 00:43:02.418
cancer-restricted cryptic antigens were shared by two or more patients,

633
00:43:02.798 --> 00:43:06.458
with a subset actually shared in over 70% of

634
00:43:06.498 --> 00:43:09.038
A*02:01 positive patients. This

635
00:43:10.318 --> 00:43:14.298
opens up the potential for off-the-shelf therapies if we can

636
00:43:14.338 --> 00:43:16.818
actually provoke a CD8 T cell response against them.

637
00:43:17.098 --> 00:43:20.888
And so again, to directly ask the question, can these be immunogenic,

638
00:43:21.338 --> 00:43:24.978
we first adopted and then adapted an approach to do ex

639
00:43:25.038 --> 00:43:28.798
vivo T cell priming and expansion, where we use

640
00:43:29.058 --> 00:43:32.548
HLA-matched healthy donor peripheral blood mononuclear cells,

641
00:43:32.958 --> 00:43:36.847
differentiate our own dendritic cells, use these to prime and

642
00:43:36.898 --> 00:43:40.198
expand autologous CD8 T cells, and read out

643
00:43:40.298 --> 00:43:44.168
immunogenicity using both HLA class I tetramers and effector

644
00:43:44.278 --> 00:43:48.207
cytokine secretion. We're really pleased to see that

645
00:43:48.278 --> 00:43:51.698
actually a subset of these non-canonical peptides did show

646
00:43:51.778 --> 00:43:55.658
immunogenic potential. About a quarter of them were positive in

647
00:43:55.698 --> 00:43:59.478
these assays, but actually much more excited when we broke these

648
00:43:59.598 --> 00:44:03.338
up into which were predicted to be cancer restricted

649
00:44:03.378 --> 00:44:06.178
versus non-cancer restricted based on our platform.

650
00:44:06.258 --> 00:44:10.198
As one would hope, the cancer restricted fraction was highly enriched

651
00:44:10.238 --> 00:44:14.058
in immunogenic peptides, although I highlight that we were theoretically able

652
00:44:14.098 --> 00:44:18.018
to break tolerance to a small set of non-cancer restricted

653
00:44:18.298 --> 00:44:19.238
cryptic peptides.

654
00:44:20.098 --> 00:44:22.698
We really wanted to benchmark this against more classic

655
00:44:25.758 --> 00:44:29.388
neoantigens, and so empirically tested all of

656
00:44:29.718 --> 00:44:33.638
the directly identified mutation-encoded neoepitopes, as

657
00:44:33.698 --> 00:44:36.978
well as a set of computationally predicted

658
00:44:37.038 --> 00:44:40.658
neoantigens. Clearly, mutations can be immunogenic.

659
00:44:40.738 --> 00:44:44.078
We have seen that in humans as well already in patients,

660
00:44:44.818 --> 00:44:47.278
and firm believer still in mutations.

661
00:44:47.298 --> 00:44:50.758
But our takeaway from this data was actually that cancer-restricted cryptic

662
00:44:50.818 --> 00:44:54.618
antigens are about on par with these

663
00:44:54.878 --> 00:44:57.678
more traditional classes of neoantigens.

664
00:44:58.598 --> 00:45:02.158
So we want to go a bit further into this and actually discover T cell

665
00:45:02.178 --> 00:45:06.038
receptors specific to these neoantigens, both the mutations and the

666
00:45:06.098 --> 00:45:07.818
cancer-restricted cryptic antigens.

667
00:45:07.898 --> 00:45:11.838
To do this, we had to develop pipelines, and so using DNA

668
00:45:11.978 --> 00:45:15.898
barcoded HLA class I tetramers paired with the 10x genomics

669
00:45:15.978 --> 00:45:19.958
pipeline, we can now at scale isolate full-length

670
00:45:20.058 --> 00:45:23.698
TCR alpha beta with paired antigen specificity.

671
00:45:24.578 --> 00:45:28.018
We've done this to identify a suite of cryptic

672
00:45:28.118 --> 00:45:31.918
antigen-specific TCRs across a range of

673
00:45:31.958 --> 00:45:35.858
different biotypes, take these, and we can molecularly

674
00:45:35.898 --> 00:45:39.438
reconstruct these, and then perform CRISPR-based

675
00:45:39.498 --> 00:45:42.998
TCR redirection to create TCR T cells.

676
00:45:43.558 --> 00:45:47.318
These TCR T cells can then be put back into co-culture with the

677
00:45:47.378 --> 00:45:49.698
tumor cells from which we did the immunopeptidomics, right?

678
00:45:49.758 --> 00:45:53.578
So testing against the patient-derived organoids, can these

679
00:45:53.658 --> 00:45:57.118
actually recognize and kill tumor cells expressing

680
00:45:57.198 --> 00:46:00.158
endogenous levels of their cognate antigen?

681
00:46:00.658 --> 00:46:04.418
And that's exactly what we saw across multiple different cryptic

682
00:46:04.478 --> 00:46:08.458
antigen-specific TCRs, even targeting different biotypes.

683
00:46:08.738 --> 00:46:11.918
We saw quite exquisite cytotoxicity, even at low

684
00:46:12.318 --> 00:46:16.278
effector-to-target ratios. We've now done this in vitro as

685
00:46:16.338 --> 00:46:20.258
cell lines, ex vivo as patient-derived organoids, but also

686
00:46:20.418 --> 00:46:24.258
in vivo using randomized and blinded preclinical studies to

687
00:46:24.298 --> 00:46:28.168
test adoptive cell therapy using TCRT in these models,

688
00:46:28.578 --> 00:46:31.978
demonstrating, again, for the first time that cryptic antigen-specific

689
00:46:32.038 --> 00:46:35.958
TCRs can exert tumorocidal activity in any

690
00:46:36.018 --> 00:46:39.538
cancer type, in fact. But this, I will say, is proof of concept.

691
00:46:39.578 --> 00:46:43.418
This was truly TCR001, the first one we ever

692
00:46:43.478 --> 00:46:47.238
identified, and we were able to profoundly delay tumor progression,

693
00:46:47.558 --> 00:46:50.898
but not completely eradicate these tumors, and I think that's important to

694
00:46:50.958 --> 00:46:54.698
highlight. So now in unpublished work, we've tried to expand this and ask the

695
00:46:54.758 --> 00:46:57.538
question, well, why couldn't we eradicate these tumors?

696
00:46:57.898 --> 00:47:01.138
And so one question is, is the actual antigen

697
00:47:01.238 --> 00:47:04.298
heterogeneity. So we've now been testing

698
00:47:04.378 --> 00:47:07.717
combinations of targeting multiple

699
00:47:07.878 --> 00:47:11.818
distinct cancer-restricted cryptic antigens, showing that these can actually

700
00:47:11.837 --> 00:47:15.538
augment cytotoxicity against patient-derived

701
00:47:15.598 --> 00:47:19.158
PDOC organoids. Here, even in long-term IncuCyte

702
00:47:19.318 --> 00:47:23.278
assays, just targeting just two can nearly eradicate

703
00:47:23.288 --> 00:47:24.718
these patient-derived organoids.

704
00:47:24.748 --> 00:47:28.518
So we think that this is a very exciting time and really poised for

705
00:47:28.558 --> 00:47:29.808
clinical translation.

706
00:47:31.078 --> 00:47:34.418
So let me just summarize, hopefully convince you all that this

707
00:47:34.918 --> 00:47:38.358
newer class of non-canonical HLA-1 bound

708
00:47:38.398 --> 00:47:41.918
peptides are abundant in the pancreatic cancer

709
00:47:41.978 --> 00:47:45.618
immunopeptidome. A subset of these are cancer

710
00:47:45.718 --> 00:47:49.418
restricted, shared across patients, and harbor

711
00:47:49.538 --> 00:47:53.498
robust immunogenic potential. A subset of these, we

712
00:47:53.538 --> 00:47:57.218
can find cryptic antigen-specific TCRs that are

713
00:47:57.298 --> 00:48:01.078
actually able to recognize and kill tumor cells, importantly

714
00:48:01.148 --> 00:48:03.938
expressing endogenous levels of their peptide.

715
00:48:05.298 --> 00:48:07.958
So quickly, just to thank the people who actually did the work.

