838
00:55:18.342 --> 00:55:21.022
And so this is a major challenge when you're targeting a glycan.

839
00:55:21.062 --> 00:55:23.282
It's not a single protein or a single epitope.

840
00:55:23.592 --> 00:55:27.342
Again, it's present multiple times on one protein on hundreds of different

841
00:55:27.362 --> 00:55:31.162
proteins. And so the levels in which CA19-9 accumulates in your circulation is

842
00:55:31.202 --> 00:55:35.082
extremely high. And so not only am I interested in the CA19-9

843
00:55:35.142 --> 00:55:38.462
pericentrin cascade due to cool biology, but also as

844
00:55:38.861 --> 00:55:40.882
alternative therapeutic interception points.

845
00:55:41.272 --> 00:55:45.262
And so what we found is that you block CA19-9 with this antibody, and you normalize

846
00:55:45.282 --> 00:55:47.582
the histologic architecture of the pancreas.

847
00:55:47.642 --> 00:55:50.822
You have a slight decrease in collagen deposition, but you see this profound

848
00:55:50.842 --> 00:55:54.522
reduction in both proliferation and fibroblast infiltration.

849
00:55:55.642 --> 00:55:57.842
So how? Well,

850
00:55:58.842 --> 00:56:02.442
we did the really expensive experiment in my lab, which was perhaps a mistake

851
00:56:02.862 --> 00:56:06.722
now in hindsight. We did the single-cell RNAseq experiment at the three-day

852
00:56:06.782 --> 00:56:10.682
time point, and using these advanced algorithms like Cell Chat

853
00:56:10.722 --> 00:56:12.772
and NicheNet, what we could see is that there was this

854
00:56:13.922 --> 00:56:17.722
interaction network that was strengthened when we turned on CA19-9, where you

855
00:56:17.782 --> 00:56:20.902
have ductal cells interacting more with these type of CAFs called

856
00:56:20.962 --> 00:56:24.742
