01:06:35.294 --> 01:06:36.914
If it'll start, start. Okay, here we go.

1027
01:06:37.974 --> 01:06:41.374
Okay. Early detection and interception of pancreas cancer.

1028
01:06:42.914 --> 01:06:46.254
So we are all excited about the improvements in survival of this disease.

1029
01:06:46.294 --> 01:06:50.134
When I started my lab, the five-year survival was 4%.

1030
01:06:50.174 --> 01:06:53.354
It's now 12%. Oh, sorry. My disclosure slide.

1031
01:06:53.474 --> 01:06:55.694
I'm a pathologist, so really not much to disclose here.

1032
01:06:56.474 --> 01:06:57.274
But anyway,

1033
01:06:58.114 --> 01:07:01.554
it is important to emphasize, and this is a very sobering

1034
01:07:02.594 --> 01:07:06.474
review that was done by Lola Rahib and Barbara Kenners and others, showing

1035
01:07:06.514 --> 01:07:10.174
that much of that improvement has actually come from localized

1036
01:07:10.214 --> 01:07:14.014
disease. Improvements are almost entirely because of the improvements we've

1037
01:07:14.034 --> 01:07:17.894
made in that percentage of patients with surgically resectable tumors.

1038
01:07:18.244 --> 01:07:21.874
And this is further emphasized here, where the chemotherapy

1039
01:07:22.014 --> 01:07:25.514
backbones that we have that Shubham talked about, the one-year

1040
01:07:25.594 --> 01:07:29.554
survival has improved because they do work well in that initial one-year

1041
01:07:29.654 --> 01:07:33.474
period. But then when you look at the five-year survival, this upward trajectory is

1042
01:07:33.514 --> 01:07:37.474
really for localized disease. The advanced disease is still mostly a flat

1043
01:07:37.554 --> 01:07:40.834
line. Again, this is all pre-RAS inhibitors.

1044
01:07:40.934 --> 01:07:44.694
It'll be very interesting to revisit this analysis in about a decade

1045
01:07:44.774 --> 01:07:48.534
when these inhibitors are widely available outside of the context of clinical

1046
01:07:48.614 --> 01:07:50.654
trials, but this is the reality today.

1047
01:07:52.094 --> 01:07:55.554
When we look at the trajectory of CA19-9, now I am talking about

1048
01:07:55.634 --> 01:07:59.234
old-fashioned biomarker CA19-9, not all the lovely data that Danny

1049
01:07:59.294 --> 01:07:59.794
presented.

1050
01:08:01.034 --> 01:08:04.924
You can see that almost a year before the clinical diagnosis, this was

1051
01:08:04.934 --> 01:08:05.964
done using

1052
01:08:07.214 --> 01:08:11.174
samples obtained from the PLCO repository, which has pre-diagnostic

1053
01:08:11.194 --> 01:08:14.554
samples of individuals being followed over time, so there are individuals who gave

1054
01:08:14.614 --> 01:08:18.254
blood samples and then at variable time points developed pancreas cancer.

1055
01:08:18.674 --> 01:08:22.414
So you can see that about a year before the clinical diagnosis, the

1056
01:08:22.454 --> 01:08:24.474
CA19-9 trajectory keeps going up,

1057
01:08:25.634 --> 01:08:29.574
suggesting that there is the possibility of diagnosing this disease even at

1058
01:08:29.614 --> 01:08:33.574
an occult stage. So the question that you can

1059
01:08:33.695 --> 01:08:36.235
ask, obviously is why not screen everyone above 50?

1060
01:08:36.294 --> 01:08:39.934
We do mammograms, colonoscopies. Why don't we do a CA19-9?

1061
01:08:40.434 --> 01:08:44.195
Well, the US Preventive Services Task Force, which is a

1062
01:08:44.254 --> 01:08:45.174
body tasked with

1063
01:08:46.114 --> 01:08:50.094
developing evidence-based screening guidelines, basically gives screening for

1064
01:08:50.174 --> 01:08:53.905
pancreas cancer in the general population a grade of D, which is a

1065
01:08:53.914 --> 01:08:57.614
failing grade, because not only is it not going to be helpful, it might actually do

1066
01:08:57.674 --> 01:09:01.494
harm. And this is a little piece of data that I got from Brian Volkman, who,

1067
01:09:01.554 --> 01:09:05.334
when he's not giving plenary talks on phase three trials, actually

1068
01:09:05.374 --> 01:09:07.874
thinks deeply about early detection.

1069
01:09:08.494 --> 01:09:10.294
And as you can see here,

1070
01:09:11.574 --> 01:09:15.235
the most important thing about a biomarker test

1071
01:09:15.794 --> 01:09:19.434
is not just the sensitivity and the specificity, which are the performance

1072
01:09:19.514 --> 01:09:23.294
criteria we are always thinking about, but the positive predictive value or

1073
01:09:23.414 --> 01:09:27.074
PPV. And the PPV is entirely defined by the

1074
01:09:27.114 --> 01:09:30.114
population in which that test is done.

1075
01:09:30.174 --> 01:09:34.065
So the less the prevalence of a particular entity

1076
01:09:34.094 --> 01:09:37.834
in that population where you're testing, the lower will be the PPV, which

1077
01:09:37.874 --> 01:09:41.634
means the lower is the chance that the entity

1078
01:09:41.674 --> 01:09:44.594
is actually present when the test is positive.

1079
01:09:45.004 --> 01:09:48.315
So in the general population, you could have a fantastic test, 90%

1080
01:09:48.355 --> 01:09:52.174
sensitive, 99% specific, but the PPV

1081
01:09:52.235 --> 01:09:54.235
of that will be very low in single digits.

1082
01:09:54.674 --> 01:09:58.634
Now you apply it to a little bit more enriched population, the PPV goes up,

1083
01:09:58.914 --> 01:10:02.754
and you apply to even more of an enriched population, the PPV goes up much,

1084
01:10:02.814 --> 01:10:06.714
much higher, to the point where you feel confident that a test is truly

1085
01:10:06.814 --> 01:10:10.754
positive when it's positive. And this is the reason why, and this is a whole

1086
01:10:10.874 --> 01:10:14.634
separate story altogether, it's a one-hour lecture by itself, why I have deep

1087
01:10:14.674 --> 01:10:18.634
concerns about just going out and doing ctDNA assays for pancreas cancer

1088
01:10:18.694 --> 01:10:22.154
in the general population because the PPV is going to be really low.

1089
01:10:23.254 --> 01:10:26.994
So then what do we have to do? We have to enrich these populations,

1090
01:10:27.354 --> 01:10:31.314
and that enrichment will come from defining who are high-risk cohorts

1091
01:10:31.354 --> 01:10:32.734
for pancreas cancer. Who are they?

1092
01:10:33.334 --> 01:10:37.014
So the first most common one that we know that is well defined is

1093
01:10:37.054 --> 01:10:39.734
mucinous pancreatic cysts, patients who have these

1094
01:10:41.274 --> 01:10:43.314
fluid-filled sacs in the pancreas called

1095
01:10:44.234 --> 01:10:47.794
most commonly intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms or IPMNs.

1096
01:10:49.054 --> 01:10:52.713
And there are millions of us walking around with these silent IPMNs.

1097
01:10:53.034 --> 01:10:56.514
Approximately 15% of cancers annually arise in the

1098
01:10:56.674 --> 01:11:00.154
backdrop of these IPMNs. This is an example of a high-grade

1099
01:11:00.194 --> 01:11:02.914
IPMN that just had incipient invasion.

1100
01:11:02.974 --> 01:11:04.734
This is exactly what you want to catch.

1101
01:11:05.114 --> 01:11:09.034
Catch this pre-cancer before it becomes cancer.

1102
01:11:09.064 --> 01:11:12.534
And then you have individuals who have germline mutations that puts them at

1103
01:11:12.574 --> 01:11:16.194
variable lifetime risk for pancreatic cancer, including

1104
01:11:16.374 --> 01:11:19.874
mutations like BRCA1, BRCA2, and ATM, et cetera.

1105
01:11:20.164 --> 01:11:23.924
And again, the risk varies depending on the specific alteration, but

1106
01:11:23.954 --> 01:11:27.794
approximately 10% of pancreatic cancers arise in the backdrop

1107
01:11:28.094 --> 01:11:31.334
of these germline mutations. So that's 10 plus 15, 25%.

1108
01:11:31.654 --> 01:11:35.394
What about the other 75%? The so-called sporadic pancreas cancer, the

1109
01:11:35.434 --> 01:11:36.774
patient who just walks in and

1110
01:11:37.594 --> 01:11:38.954
gets diagnosed with pancreas cancer.

1111
01:11:39.374 --> 01:11:42.994
So there we do have some indicators of potential

1112
01:11:43.154 --> 01:11:46.844
high-risk factors that we could take into account, and one of which is new

1113
01:11:46.914 --> 01:11:50.834
onset hyperglycemia and diabetes, which can be a harbinger

1114
01:11:50.874 --> 01:11:54.024
of an underlying pancreas cancer or an incipient pancreas cancer.

1115
01:11:54.414 --> 01:11:58.294
So it turns out that about a quarter of patients have full on

1116
01:11:58.774 --> 01:12:02.654
new onset diabetes months to a couple of years before the diagnosis

1117
01:12:02.694 --> 01:12:06.274
of pancreas cancer, but a much larger number have some or

1118
01:12:06.474 --> 01:12:10.414
other dysglycemia, whether it's impaired glucose tolerance

1119
01:12:10.474 --> 01:12:14.014
or pre-diabetes or something going on with their glycemic control

1120
01:12:14.334 --> 01:12:18.294
that happens months to years before the diagnosis of pancreatic cancer.

1121
01:12:19.114 --> 01:12:23.094
And really, a tribute to Suresh Chari, who was at Mayo

1122
01:12:23.154 --> 01:12:25.514
Clinic for almost three decades, who really has

1123
01:12:27.154 --> 01:12:30.694
identified this relationship between hyperglycemia and diabetes

1124
01:12:30.814 --> 01:12:34.394
preceding cancer diagnosis. You can see right here, patients with pancreas cancer,

1125
01:12:34.474 --> 01:12:38.184
this is when the cancer is diagnosed, and you can start seeing the

1126
01:12:38.274 --> 01:12:42.214
loss of glycemic control that happens months to at least a couple of years before

1127
01:12:42.514 --> 01:12:45.434
the diagnosis. All the major papers are listed

1128
01:12:45.514 --> 01:12:49.490
here.And this has been validated by many groups

1129
01:12:49.570 --> 01:12:50.930
in retrospective data.

1130
01:12:51.930 --> 01:12:53.750
You can see some of the papers here.

1131
01:12:53.790 --> 01:12:57.670
And even when there have been AI-based algorithms that have been

1132
01:12:57.690 --> 01:12:59.310
developed, this one is

1133
01:13:01.310 --> 01:13:02.210
from Dana-Farber,

1134
01:13:03.470 --> 01:13:05.650
that was published in "Nature Medicine" a few years back.

