is to really define who

1171
01:15:13.890 --> 01:15:17.730
are these subsets of individuals in whom we can enable

1172
01:15:18.130 --> 01:15:19.640
biomarker studies to

1173
01:15:20.850 --> 01:15:24.250
facilitate early detection. So this is the who, the clinical risk groups,

1174
01:15:25.150 --> 01:15:28.630
those with family history, new onset diabetes, mucinous cystic lesions.

1175
01:15:28.670 --> 01:15:32.090
I didn't talk about chronic pancreatitis. That's again an area that Danny studies.

1176
01:15:33.090 --> 01:15:34.770
And then the how is the biomarkers.

1177
01:15:34.890 --> 01:15:38.830
CA19-9 is obviously the old guard, but now a lot of new

1178
01:15:38.910 --> 01:15:42.170
work is going on in this area. And where is it?

1179
01:15:43.350 --> 01:15:47.030
Where is the lesion? And this is where obviously a lot of work is

1180
01:15:47.090 --> 01:15:50.950
ongoing in terms of radiomics and AI to better find those

1181
01:15:51.010 --> 01:15:54.110
tiny lesions that would be missed by the radiologist's eye.

1182
01:15:54.690 --> 01:15:58.630
And so just to give a plug for the role of AI in this entire

1183
01:15:58.770 --> 01:16:02.710
journey, Eric Topol and I wrote this little one-pager a couple of years

1184
01:16:02.750 --> 01:16:06.710
back. There's a lot of AI at this meeting, but I really think this is

1185
01:16:06.770 --> 01:16:10.710
an area where AI, beginning with identification of who is

1186
01:16:10.870 --> 01:16:14.379
at risk, starting with mining electronic health records,

1187
01:16:14.990 --> 01:16:18.870
to using it to identify patterns in liquid biopsies such as

1188
01:16:18.950 --> 01:16:22.190
fragmentomic patterns for tiny lesions, to

1189
01:16:22.250 --> 01:16:26.030
AI-enabled imaging and improving the resolution of a

1190
01:16:26.070 --> 01:16:29.790
human eye would be very, very important. So lots of work ongoing here.

1191
01:16:29.930 --> 01:16:33.790
Just wanted to give a landscape view before I pivot to the

1192
01:16:33.830 --> 01:16:36.190
second half of my talk, which is on interception.

1193
01:16:37.070 --> 01:16:40.050
So early detection of pancreatic cancer in high-risk cohorts.

1194
01:16:40.110 --> 01:16:42.310
So many, many academic centers

1195
01:16:43.770 --> 01:16:47.750
in the country run these surveillance studies where

1196
01:16:47.790 --> 01:16:51.590
individuals who have germline mutations or who have cystic

1197
01:16:51.630 --> 01:16:55.430
lesions, they come in, they get an imaging study done, maybe

1198
01:16:55.490 --> 01:16:59.430
get a CA19-9 drawn, and then they're told to come back in six months or a

1199
01:16:59.530 --> 01:17:02.250
year. But it's really very passive follow-up.

1200
01:17:02.330 --> 01:17:04.849
We don't really do anything for these individuals.

1201
01:17:05.370 --> 01:17:09.270
Yet it's a very motivated group, amazing performance status in

1202
01:17:09.310 --> 01:17:13.230
most individuals. These are not patients with cancer, and so they

1203
01:17:13.290 --> 01:17:17.250
really want something done. And so is there an opportunity to do something actively

1204
01:17:17.290 --> 01:17:20.960
for these individuals? And this is where the concept of interception comes in,

1205
01:17:21.070 --> 01:17:24.890
which is a way of basically stopping cancer in its tracks.

1206
01:17:25.230 --> 01:17:26.990
The foundational commentary

1207
01:17:28.010 --> 01:17:31.890
was written by Elizabeth Blackburn, the Nobel laureate for telomerase,

1208
01:17:31.950 --> 01:17:35.220
and she came up with this term cancer interception,

1209
01:17:35.870 --> 01:17:39.510
literally based on interception in football, in American

1210
01:17:39.550 --> 01:17:43.330
football. And if you look at the commentary, there is a figure of

1211
01:17:44.490 --> 01:17:45.930
the quarterback being intercepted.

1212
01:17:46.330 --> 01:17:49.150
So it literally is based on that particular analogy.

1213
01:17:50.530 --> 01:17:53.130
So the question is: Can we intercept pancreas cancer?

1214
01:17:53.970 --> 01:17:57.770
And so I want to talk about a couple of vignettes. One is vaccines.

1215
01:17:58.410 --> 01:18:01.590
So this was preclinical work that was done in the lab of

1216
01:18:02.550 --> 01:18:04.050
Liz Jaffee at Hopkins.

1217
01:18:05.150 --> 01:18:08.650
Her grad student and I spent a lot of time on the microscope

1218
01:18:08.810 --> 01:18:12.110
measuring the PanIN lesions in these mice that got a Listeria-based

1219
01:18:12.190 --> 01:18:14.489
vaccine. That's the paper that was published.

1220
01:18:14.820 --> 01:18:18.370
And based on that data that showed that a vaccine was able to

1221
01:18:18.410 --> 01:18:20.890
attenuate PanIN progression in this mouse model,

1222
01:18:22.030 --> 01:18:24.450
Liz and our colleagues launched this.

1223
01:18:24.850 --> 01:18:28.799
Initially, this was a study that was done in patients who underwent surgical

1224
01:18:28.830 --> 01:18:32.570
resection, so they were diagnosed with cancer, underwent resection, and then

1225
01:18:32.610 --> 01:18:36.250
received the vaccine in adjuvant setting just for safety and feasibility purposes.

1226
01:18:36.590 --> 01:18:40.210
This is very similar to the ELISIO trial that Shubham talked

1227
01:18:40.270 --> 01:18:44.050
about or the mRNA vaccine trial that

1228
01:18:44.530 --> 01:18:48.370
Vinod talked about. These are all individuals who already got diagnosed, underwent

1229
01:18:48.430 --> 01:18:51.830
surgery, and got the vaccine in their adjuvant setting or in the

1230
01:18:52.370 --> 01:18:56.366
neo-adjuvant setting.But then the question is, can you do this

1231
01:18:56.426 --> 01:18:59.266
in a non-cancer high-risk context?

1232
01:18:59.646 --> 01:19:00.046
And this is

1233
01:19:01.326 --> 01:19:05.046
really the girl boss team of cancer vaccines at

1234
01:19:05.086 --> 01:19:07.426
Hopkins, Liz, Neha, Nilo, and Amanda.

1235
01:19:08.346 --> 01:19:11.886
And they were funded initially through the Stand Up to Cancer Lost Garden

1236
01:19:11.966 --> 01:19:15.586
Foundation, ACR Interception Dream Team, which I had the privilege of leading.

1237
01:19:15.616 --> 01:19:18.606
And actually, Will was also a part of that team when he was in Tyler's lab.

1238
01:19:19.386 --> 01:19:23.346
And this began the first vaccine trial targeted against mutant

1239
01:19:23.366 --> 01:19:23.826
KRAS.

1240
01:19:25.226 --> 01:19:28.726
It was a synthetic long peptide, SLP vaccine, against the six common

1241
01:19:28.766 --> 01:19:29.406
mutations,

1242
01:19:30.266 --> 01:19:34.046
and was done in patients who were high risk because they had germline mutations.

1243
01:19:34.086 --> 01:19:37.726
They didn't have necessarily discernible lesions in the

1244
01:19:37.766 --> 01:19:38.186
pancreas,

1245
01:19:39.446 --> 01:19:42.446
or they may have had something suspicious, but they didn't have cancer.

1246
01:19:43.226 --> 01:19:46.006
And so this is just one piece of data I wanted to share.

1247
01:19:46.066 --> 01:19:50.046
This is courtesy of Neha Zaidi, who really is leading all of these efforts at

1248
01:19:50.086 --> 01:19:53.906
Hopkins. So in these patients, again, these are high-risk individuals who

1249
01:19:54.066 --> 01:19:57.666
don't have cancer, vaccination with a KRAS vaccine

1250
01:19:57.726 --> 01:19:58.426
induces

1251
01:20:00.646 --> 01:20:02.816
mutant KRAS-specific T-cell responses.

1252
01:20:03.186 --> 01:20:04.806
Remember, there are no tissues here.

1253
01:20:05.806 --> 01:20:09.646
The only surrogate you have of immune response here is what you

1254
01:20:09.686 --> 01:20:13.326
can find from PBMCs. But what you can see here

1255
01:20:13.446 --> 01:20:17.246
is more than 90% of patients developed at least

1256
01:20:17.366 --> 01:20:19.716
some mutant KRAS-specific T-cell responses.

1257
01:20:20.186 --> 01:20:24.046
More than 80% developed them against all six antigens, all

1258
01:20:24.106 --> 01:20:28.026
six KRAS antigens, all the colors you see on those bars that they were

1259
01:20:28.066 --> 01:20:31.926
vaccinated against. And this is the most exciting piece of the data.

1260
01:20:32.026 --> 01:20:35.686
Ultimately, interception depends on longevity of the response, and you heard that

1261
01:20:35.786 --> 01:20:39.466
from the talk that Vinod gave that was featured on NBC

1262
01:20:39.546 --> 01:20:43.466
News, that six years after vaccination, these patients had lasting

1263
01:20:43.526 --> 01:20:47.506
T-cell responses. We're not that far along, but you can see here that

1264
01:20:47.666 --> 01:20:51.426
one year after vaccination, again, these patients got three prime

1265
01:20:51.486 --> 01:20:53.246
doses and one boost, and that was it.

1266
01:20:53.786 --> 01:20:56.446
Still, one year later, they still have persistent

1267
01:20:56.846 --> 01:21:00.366
KRAS-specific T-cell responses in the blood

1268
01:21:00.586 --> 01:21:03.326
suggesting that there is ongoing immune activity.

1269
01:21:03.406 --> 01:21:07.386
Now, again, whether there'll be a clinical readout, this is obviously a lot more

1270
01:21:07.466 --> 01:21:11.246
challenging than a recurrence setting where the runway is

1271
01:21:11.306 --> 01:21:14.126
shorter, but at least we know that these T-cells are there.

1272
01:21:16.006 --> 01:21:18.326
Okay, KRAS inhibitors. I got to talk about that.

1273
01:21:19.106 --> 01:21:21.866
So can you do interception with KRAS inhibitors?

1274
01:21:22.006 --> 01:21:25.846
So in 2023 with Raghu Kalluri at MD Anderson, when I was there, we published this

1275
01:21:25.866 --> 01:21:29.846
initial study, and that was with MRTX1133, a great preclinical

1276
01:21:29.926 --> 01:21:32.346
drug that unfortunately did not make it to the clinic.

1277
01:21:33.346 --> 01:21:37.146
But you can see that this is a G12D inhibitor, and this is a

1278
01:21:37.186 --> 01:21:40.426
KC mouse. So those of you who study the disease, this is a G12D

1279
01:21:40.466 --> 01:21:44.086
model. And you can see very nice attenuation of panins when

1280
01:21:44.106 --> 01:21:47.786
the treatment is started early. You can see, it's complete

1281
01:21:47.846 --> 01:21:50.006
disappearance, to be honest, of all panins here.

1282
01:21:51.746 --> 01:21:55.546
He has since done this now with the RevMed-9805

1283
01:21:55.566 --> 01:21:57.706
drug, which is again, the G12D inhibitor.

1284
01:21:57.726 --> 01:22:01.576
And again, you can see very nicely, in the KC model, which is

1285
01:22:01.666 --> 01:22:04.896
just the KRAS disappearance of the panin lesions.

1286
01:22:05.336 --> 01:22:08.956
And then in the KPC model, which also has p53 and has much

1287
01:22:09.066 --> 01:22:12.966
faster progression, same thing. With this early treatment, you get

1288
01:22:13.006 --> 01:22:16.786
regression of panin lesions. Today, in just a

1289
01:22:16.866 --> 01:22:20.775
little bit, Minh Tan, I don't know if he's in the audience, but from

1290
01:22:21.346 --> 01:22:25.286
Penn with Bob Vonderheide and Ben Stanger, just published this paper

1291
01:22:25.346 --> 01:22:28.986
in Science on cancer interception with KRAS inhibitors in the

1292
01:22:29.026 --> 01:22:33.006
KPC model. And they used tool compounds that are basically

1293
01:22:33.046 --> 01:22:36.706
the tool compounds for deraxone, rasib, and zoldanrasib.

1294
01:22:37.266 --> 01:22:38.946
And he's going to talk about this this afternoon.

1295
01:22:38.976 --> 01:22:42.026
I encourage you to go and listen to his talk if you can.

1296
01:22:42.586 --> 01:22:44.606
Ben Neil and I wrote an editorial

1297
01:22:45.406 --> 01:22:49.146
as an accompaniment to this. And the bottom line is they really

1298
01:22:49.286 --> 01:22:53.206
primed this strategy for the clinic, if you so

1299
01:22:53.306 --> 01:22:56.986
will. And there's a couple of nuances here that they did that I think is

1300
01:22:57.046 --> 01:23:00.806
helpful as we consider moving this strategy to the clinic.

1301
01:23:00.986 --> 01:23:04.686
One is that they showed that even brief periods of dosing were

1302
01:23:04.726 --> 01:23:08.396
effective in reducing pre-cancer burden, which again, is something that you might

1303
01:23:08.426 --> 01:23:12.136
think about when we translate to humans, like, do they have to take this

1304
01:23:12.166 --> 01:23:14.806
lifelong or can we do short bursts and then stop?

1305
01:23:15.326 --> 01:23:19.146
And the second is this metronomic dosing, one week off, one week on, which is

1306
01:23:19.386 --> 01:23:23.296
like drug holidays we do in patients for reducing toxicity that

1307
01:23:23.306 --> 01:23:24.906
Shubham talked about in his talk.

1308
01:23:26.566 --> 01:23:27.486
My last slide.

1309
01:23:28.306 --> 01:23:31.406
As the chair, I think I have a little bit of prerogative to go rogue.

1310
01:23:32.366 --> 01:23:35.896
And I'm on the West Coast. So biohacking

1311
01:23:35.946 --> 01:23:39.606
KRAS. We are all here amongst biohackers.

